Nevertheless, challenges associated with quality and density of observation as well as the complexity of physical mechanisms underlying energy release have hindered an automatic and timely analysis framework, often still relying (in part) on human visual inspection and parameter tuning. We introduce a feature extraction framework for energetic fingerprints, built from unsupervised, denoising-based audio signal processing methods, which facilitates the direct identification and quantification of physical properties of the former. Thereby, the need for human expertise or large datasets to inform machine learning approaches is circumvented, while additionally enabling the automation of time-localized feature labeling and energetic classification. In particular, we demonstrate that solar flare triggering can be conducted effectively and efficiently without any a priori assumptions or training data as a direct result of this approach.
